ğŸ”¹ Azure Hierarchy in Detail
Azure Account (identity / login)
   â””â”€â”€ Subscription (billing boundary, quota limits, RBAC scope)
         â””â”€â”€ Resource Group (logical container for lifecycle management)
               â””â”€â”€ Virtual Network (VNet = isolated private network space)
                     â””â”€â”€ Subnet (smaller IP segment of VNet)
                           â””â”€â”€ Resources (VMs, NICs, DBs, Storage, etc.)
1ï¸âƒ£ Azure Account
Your identity (email or service principal).
Linked to Azure Active Directory.
Can own multiple subscriptions.

2ï¸âƒ£ Subscription
Billing unit â€” all usage inside is billed here.
Also defines limits (cores, storage, etc.).
Example: Dev-Sub, Prod-Sub.

3ï¸âƒ£ Resource Group
Logical grouping of resources for lifecycle management.
Delete RG â†’ all resources inside are deleted.
Can contain: VNets, VMs, DBs, Storage accounts, etc.

4ï¸âƒ£ Virtual Network (VNet)
Network boundary inside a resource group.
Defines IP address space (like 10.0.0.0/16).
Can connect to other VNets, on-prem, or internet.

5ï¸âƒ£ Subnet
Smaller CIDR blocks inside a VNet.
Segregates resources logically (e.g., Web Tier, App Tier, DB Tier).
Example:

10.0.1.0/24 â†’ Web servers

10.0.2.0/24 â†’ Databases

6ï¸âƒ£ Resources
Actual services running inside the subnet.

Examples:
VMs (Compute)
NICs (Networking)
DBs (Databases)
Storage Accounts (Storage)

A good way to remember is:
Account â†’ Subscription â†’ Resource Group â†’ VNet â†’ Subnet â†’ Resources
